{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540204"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:52:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:52:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16750"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16750"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.55,0.07,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102096"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84541"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1901"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"2936"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"3101"},{"type":"tags","id":"3123"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43658"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102096"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of increased energy, irritability, and difficulty sleeping. Her partner reports she has been sleeping only four hours per night but remains energetic during the day. She has been more talkative than usual and has spent $3,000 on unnecessary household items. She has no previous psychiatric history. Her medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). She was prescribed prednisolone 37.5 mg daily for a COPD exacerbation six weeks ago, which was intended as a 5-day course. However, further history reveals that she had continued to take it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears restless with mildly pressured speech. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination is normal. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence lithium","Arrange psychological counselling","Reduce prednisolone dose","Start quetiapine","Immediately cease prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms of hypomania/mild mania in the context of prolonged exogenous corticosteroid use. The first step in management should be addressing the underlying cause - the iatrogenic Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing prednisolone dose\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step, as the psychiatric symptoms are likely secondary to cortisol excess. This should be done gradually to prevent adrenal crisis, as the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis may be suppressed after six weeks of high-dose glucocorticoids. The patient should be educated about the importance of not stopping glucocorticoids abruptly and the need for tapering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELithium\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective mood stabiliser for bipolar affective disorder, but would not address the underlying cause in this case. Additionally, starting lithium without first addressing the cortisol excess could complicate the clinical picture and expose the patient to unnecessary medication side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E might help control acute symptoms but would not address the underlying cause. While antipsychotics might be needed temporarily for severe symptoms, they should not be the first-line treatment when there is a clear organic cause that can be addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychological counselling\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient for managing mood symptoms with an organic cause, particularly when there is an identifiable endocrine abnormality that needs to be addressed. However, it may be beneficial as an adjunctive treatment once the glucocorticoid dose has been appropriately reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediately cease prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous and potentially life-threatening. Abrupt cessation of corticosteroids after prolonged use can lead to adrenal crisis due to suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis. This can result in hypotension, hypoglycaemia, electrolyte abnormalities, and even death. A gradual taper is essential to allow the adrenal glands to resume normal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECushing\u0027s syndrome, whether endogenous or iatrogenic, can present with various psychiatric manifestations including mood elevation, depression, anxiety, irritability, and insomnia. The key to management is recognising the association between cortisol excess and psychiatric symptoms, and addressing the underlying cause while providing appropriate supportive care. In this case, the patient inadvertently continued a short-term glucocorticoid course for much longer than intended, leading to iatrogenic Cushing\u0027s syndrome with psychiatric manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cushing\u0027s syndrome can present with psychiatric manifestations including mood changes, irritability, and insomnia.","The presence of classical cushingoid features should prompt consideration of endocrine causes in new-onset psychiatric presentations.","Cortisol excess must be treated to achieve resolution of psychiatric symptoms in Cushing\u0027s syndrome.","Gradual tapering of corticosteroids is essential to prevent adrenal crisis while addressing iatrogenic Cushing\u0027s syndrome."],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry.","Elshimy G, Chippa V, Kaur J, et al. Adrenal Crisis. [Updated 2025 Feb 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499968/","Pelewicz K, Mi\u015bkiewicz P. Glucocorticoid Withdrawal-An Overview on When and How to Diagnose Adrenal Insufficiency in Clinical Practice. Diagnostics (Basel). 2021 Apr 20;11(4):728. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics11040728. PMID: 33923971; PMCID: PMC8072923. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33923971/","Reincke M, Fleseriu M. Cushing Syndrome: A Review. JAMA. 2023 Jul 11;330(2):170-181. doi: 10.1001/jama.2023.11305. PMID: 37432427. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37432427/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84541"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84541"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T16:50:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T15:37:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9441"}},"content